<br>
“Clark is not my ex, and he is my friend,” Chloe reminded him. Lex kept his eyes on the road. The trip back to the manor was taking longer. The roads were icier and it was beginning to snow heavily.<br>
<br>
“So you wouldn’t have any problem with Victoria coming over to the house then?” Lex smirked, but unfortunately his comment didn’t get the reaction he was looking for.<br>
<br>
“I have no problem with Victoria, as long as she doesn’t drag her boyfriend Derek along again,” she responded. Lex frowned and gripped the wheel a little tighter.<br>
<br>
“Why?” His voice was neutral but tinged with angry suspicion. Chloe shrugged.<br>
<br>
“He’s hit on me the last couple of times we’ve seen them,” she said, shaking her head with disdain. “What a creep.” Lex glanced over at Chloe.<br>
<br>
“And you’re just now telling me this? Why didn’t you tell me before?” He asked. She glanced over and gave him a small grin.<br>
<br>
“Because Victoria’s obsession with Derek is pretty much the only thing standing in the way of her trying to hook up with you again,” she said honestly. He grinned back.<br>
<br>
“That, and I’m married,” he said. Chloe laughed.<br>
<br>
“Somehow I doubt that would matter,” she responded. Lex’s expression showed that he agreed with her.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps something can be done about both of them then,” he mumbled. Chloe raised an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“I certainly hope you’re not planning anything evil,” she teased and then smiled. “At least wait until after Christmas.” Lex chuckled. He knew no other woman who would have ever said something like that to him, even if it was in a jesting manner. He looked at her with love and appreciation. The months immediately following their marriage had been a somewhat smooth transition compared to what he thought it would be like. Except for the fact that Clark still considered himself in the running, everything was great.<br>
<br>
Of course, the Clark thing was a huge thorn in his side. Not to mention the fact that Chloe seemed to truly believe that he only saw her as a friend. Hell, she believed that Clark was still in love with Lana. They did spend a lot of time together, but Lex saw the way Clark looked at Chloe. He saw the way he doted on her and became more and more protective. Lex saw the way Clark was silently assuring Chloe that he would always be there for her, preparing her to accept him after she came to her senses and got out of her marriage. Just thinking about it made him angry. Chloe smiled lovingly at him and touched his arm.<br>
<br>
“I was just kidding,” she said. He looked confused for a moment, and then remembered the after Christmas comment. “Are you okay?” Lex nodded.<br>
<br>
“Fine. Just trying to concentrate on the road,” he lied. Chloe frowned.<br>
<br>
“It is pretty bad,” she agreed.<br>
<br>
“We should have had the chauffer drive us,” Lex added as an afterthought. Chloe stared out at the contrast between the dark sky and the falling white snow.<br>
<br>
“We would have never made it there if we had taken the limo,” she said. Lex smiled.<br>
<br>
“I know.” He chuckled and she rolled her eyes but started laughing as well. Their SUV hit a patch of ice and slid a little. Chloe grasped onto the side of the door and the glove compartment as a gut reaction. Lex managed to get the situation under control again, but had to drive barely at a creeping pace to make it along the long stream of ice. Chloe rested her head back against her chair.<br>
<br>
“Not your usual speed,” she said in a half kidding voice to lighten the mood. Lex kept a neutral and concentrating look on his face. He glanced over at Chloe who was now smiling at him. He grinned.<br>
<br>
“If I went my normal speed then we’d end up under a pile of snow and probably end up getting rescued by Clark Kent,” he said. Chloe laughed.<br>
<br>
“We can’t have that then can we?” She teased. He grinned.<br>
<br>
“No.” Lex could see a pair of headlights coming down the road. From their height, it looked like a large truck. The truck was going a lot faster than they were, and it started to spin. Chloe screamed and shielded her stomach as it came hurling toward them.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Lex woke up cold and took in his surroundings. Their car was in an upright position, but had rolled a couple of times. Chloe was unconscious and her head was pushed up against the broken passenger side window. Lex cursed when he turned her head and saw the blood running down her face. He pushed aside the feelings of pain radiating from his own body. Snow was blocking too much of his view to see the truck that hit them. He unlatched his and Chloe’s safety belts. He shook her lightly.<br>
<br>
“Chloe,” he said, not bothering to use a soft voice. No response. He shook her again. “Chloe, honey, you need to get up now.” No response. Lex’s pulse raced as panic took hold of him. He reluctantly checked her pulse and let out the breath he had been holding when he found it. It seemed okay, but he didn’t know much about what was normal and what wasn’t when it came to that sort of thing.<br>
<br>
He dug the cell phone out of his jacket and tried to dial 911, and groaned when it said it couldn’t process the information. He figured the storm was messing with the cell towers somehow, but it didn’t make him feel any better. The smell of gasoline was thick in the air and he didn’t want the fumes to hurt the baby. Lex knew that their best chance for survival was to leave the vehicle, but in his weakened state he wasn’t sure he would be able to carry his unconscious wife all the way back to the Kent farm, and it was the closest residence. He growled and tried to wake her again.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Clark was pouting. Even with the bad roads, Chloe should have been home by now, which meant that she should have called to let him know that she was all right. But she hadn’t. Pete and Lana seemed to be enjoying themselves, laughing on the other side of the room. Half of him felt that he should be doing the same, but the other part, the side that usually won out, had a feeling that Chloe was in some sort of trouble and longed to help her. He grabbed his coat and rushed out the door without giving anyone an explanation.<br>
<br>
He ran quickly until he saw what looked like what had been a car accident. His heart sank. A truck was overturned and smashed against a tree. On the other side of the road, primarily obscured by the snow, was Lex and Chloe’s SUV. He used his x-ray vision and saw Lex trying to wake up Chloe. He rushed over to them and knocked on Lex’s window. Lex’s head spun around. Clark tried to discern whether it was a look of anger, but decided that it didn’t matter. He wasn’t actually here to save Lex anyway. Clark opened the door and Lex got out. Lex ran a hand over his bald and bleeding head.<br>
<br>
“There was a truck, it lost control and slammed into us,” Lex rambled. “Chloe’s hurt, I don’t know how badly, but she’s not waking up.” The panic was evident in his voice. Without saying a word, Clark went around to her side of the car to get her out. He lifted her easily into her arms.<br>
<br>
“We need to get her back to the house,” he said. Lex nodded in agreement and then looked around. A confused expression crossed his face.<br>
<br>
“Where’s your truck?”<br>
