<br>
“Uh, I didn’t take the truck Lex,” he stammered. “I ran.” Lex eyed him suspiciously.<br>
<br>
“You ran,” he repeated in disbelief. Clark nodded. He was about to say something when a familiar truck honked and headlights could be seen. Clark let out the breath he was holding in. He didn’t think his dad had seen him leave, but he thanked God that he did. Jonathan jumped out of the truck when he saw Chloe’s limp body in Clark’s arms.<br>
<br>
“Is she alright?” He asked in a worried voice. Clark frowned.<br>
<br>
“She has a pulse, but it seems to be getting weaker, and…” Jonathan interrupted his son’s rambling.<br>
<br>
“We need to get her to the hospital Clark. Put her in the truck,” Jonathan ordered. Lex glared at him.<br>
<br>
“You are not putting my pregnant wife in the back of your truck in the middle of winter,” he argued. Jonathan brushed him off.<br>
<br>
“She’s going in the cab Luthor, you and Clark ride in back.” He didn’t wait for Lex’s response and helped buckle Chloe into the passenger seat. Lex and Clark climbed into the back of the truck and they began to drive toward the hospital, both hoping that Chloe would be all right.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
They were in the waiting area for what seemed like an eternity. Dr. Schafer sighed as she walked out into the hospital’s waiting area. She already had the displeasure of being reprimanded by the administrators after she had counseled Chloe that keeping the baby wasn’t the only option. It was standard protocol, but she guessed that things like that didn’t apply to Lex Luthor, or at least he didn’t think so. She had little doubt that he would be more enraged with the information she was about to give him. Lex caught sight of her immediately and walked to her fluidly.<br>
<br>
“My wife,” he said. It was clear it was a demand for information rather than a request. Dr. Schafer tried to use her best authoritative look on him, but he wasn’t frightened into submission even a little bit.<br>
<br>
“Besides the hard blow to her head, she also suffered massive internal injury,” she started, keeping her voice as calm as possible. The men’s eyes all went wide. “We lost a heart beat twice while she was on the operating table.”<br>
<br>
“And now?” Clark asked in a panicked voice. She frowned.<br>
<br>
“We were able to contain most of Chloe’s internal bleeding, but right now it’s still touch and go. She still hasn’t woken up yet, and there’s a very real possibility that she won’t.” Dr. Schafer sighed. “There was also some damage to the amniotic sac. Currently, the baby seems to be in stable condition, but realistically, we will probably need to deliver early.” Lex paled and felt ill.<br>
<br>
“Can I see her?” Lex asked. Dr. Schafer shook her head.<br>
<br>
“She’s still in critical condition, but maybe if her status changes.” She paused. “I’ll be sure to have someone keep you updated,” she said sympathetically and turned to leave. Lex grabbed for a chair and buried his head in his hands. Clark looked stunned and flopped down in a chair across from him.<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry,” Clark said. Lex looked up at him. Clark saw his wet eyes and cringed. “I know you love her, I just…” Lex nodded in understanding.<br>
<br>
“You love her too,” he said. Clark nodded. “I know.”<br>
<br>
“And now we’re both going to lose her,” Clark said in a small voice. Lex stared at him.<br>
<br>
“Is that what you think? Geez Clark, no wonder she didn’t choose you.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Chloe could hear beeping sounds and she slowly opened her eyes to take in her surroundings. She could feel pain radiating from every part of her body and she groaned. Luckily, a nurse passing by her door heard her, and swiftly moved into her room.<br>
<br>
“You’re up!” She said excitedly. She noted her stats on a clipboard and smiled at her. “We thought for sure you weren’t going to make it.” Chloe gave an expression in between confusion and panic.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean? What happened?” She asked.<br>
<br>
“You were in a car accident sweetie, but don’t worry, the fact that you’re awake now is a very good sign,” the nurse replied. Chloe closed her eyes. She didn’t remember being in a car accident; she didn’t remember much of anything. “I’ll need to tell the doctor first, but I’m sure your husband will be very happy to hear the news.” Chloe’s eyes shot open and grew wide.<br>
<br>
“Husband?” She squeaked. The nurse grinned, not understanding that Chloe didn’t remember. She gently lifted Chloe’s left hand for her to see her large wedding ring. Chloe’s mouth dropped open.<br>
<br>
“And don’t worry, we’re still monitoring the baby,” the nurse said and sweetly patted her belly. Chloe’s eyes almost jumped out of their sockets. The nurse left and Chloe lay in her bed, trying to remember.<br>
<br>
‘Husband? I’m married? And pregnant?’ She thought. Her head was swimming. How much time had she lost? The doctor came in and Chloe couldn’t help noticing the look of relief on her face. She seemed familiar, but Chloe couldn’t place her.<br>
<br>
“How are you feeling?” Dr. Schafer asked.<br>
<br>
“Confused,” Chloe admitted.<br>
<br>
“You don’t remember the car accident?” She asked in a worried tone. Chloe shook her head.<br>
<br>
“Apparently I don’t remember anything,” Chloe answered. The doctor frowned and sat down in a chair beside her bed. She had her chart out, ready to record information.<br>
<br>
“Let’s start with your name. Do you remember that?” She asked. Chloe nodded.<br>
<br>
“Chloe Sullivan,” she said without missing a beat. The doctor frowned and Chloe tried to read her expression. “At least it was,” she added and held up her hand to show her the wedding and engagement rings that graced her finger. The doctor nodded. “How long have I been out of it?” Dr. Schafer glanced at her watch.<br>
<br>
“You were unconscious when they brought you in, so I’m guessing almost six hours now,” she answered. Chloe paled.<br>
<br>
“Then why don’t I remember?”<br>
<br>
“You suffered a lot of damage in the car accident,” the doctor started. “You were losing a lot of blood internally. We had to operate.” She paused. “You may just have some temporary amnesia associated with that.” Dr. Schafer shook her head and Chloe furrowed her brow.<br>
<br>
“What?”<br>
<br>
“Life is strange,” she observed. “I fully expected you to have amnesia the last time you came in and you didn’t, and now…” Chloe looked even more confused.<br>
<br>
“The last time?” She asked. The doctor grinned.<br>
<br>
“It’s a long story.” She stood up. “You want me to send your husband in? Seeing him might refresh your memories.” Chloe nodded. “Okay, I’ll be back to check on you later Mrs. Luthor.” She walked out of the room without noticing how large Chloe’s eyes had gotten.<br>
<br>
‘Mrs. Luthor?!’<br>
